    "details": "## Understanding Vitamin D deficiency\n\nVitamin D deficiency is a nutrigenomic finding linking your genetic variants in VDR, GC, CYP2R1 to how your body processes specific nutrients. These variants affect enzymatic activity, transport proteins, or metabolic pathways that determine your individual nutritional needs \u2014 which may differ significantly from population-wide dietary guidelines.\n\nNutrigenomics research has shown that genetic variation accounts for a substantial portion of individual differences in nutrient metabolism. What works as optimal nutrition for one person may be inadequate or excessive for another, based largely on these genetic differences.\n\n## The Genetic Connection\n\n**VDR** encodes vitamin D receptor, a nuclear receptor that mediates the genomic effects of calcitriol (active vitamin D). **GC** encodes vitamin D binding protein (GC-globulin), the main transport protein for vitamin D metabolites in blood. **CYP2R1** encodes 25-hydroxylase, the liver enzyme that performs the first hydroxylation step in vitamin D activation.\n\nThese genetic variants alter the efficiency of specific metabolic steps, meaning your body may require more of certain nutrients, convert them less efficiently, or handle them differently than standard dietary reference intakes assume.\n\n## What Your Results Mean\n\n**Elevated risk** for vitamin d deficiency indicates your genetic variants significantly reduce the efficiency of the relevant metabolic pathway. You likely need higher dietary intake or supplementation of specific nutrients to maintain optimal levels. Without targeted intervention, you may be at risk for functional deficiency even with a diet that meets standard recommended intakes.\n\n**Moderate risk** suggests partially reduced metabolic efficiency. Paying attention to dietary sources of affected nutrients and considering modest supplementation during periods of increased demand (illness, pregnancy, high physical activity) is advisable.\n\n**Typical** means your nutrient metabolism operates within normal parameters for this pathway. Standard dietary guidelines are appropriate, though whole-food-focused eating patterns remain optimal.\n\n## Actionable Insights\n\nNutritional genomics is one of the most directly actionable areas of genetic testing. Unlike disease risk (which involves complex multi-gene interactions), nutrient metabolism variants often point to specific, measurable deficiencies that can be corrected through diet and supplementation.\n\nConsider working with a registered dietitian who understands nutrigenomics to develop a personalized nutrition plan based on your genetic profile. Testing relevant biomarkers (blood levels of affected nutrients) provides concrete data to complement your genetic results.\n\nFocus on food-first strategies when possible, as nutrients from whole foods are generally better absorbed and utilized than supplements. When supplementation is warranted, choose bioavailable forms appropriate for your genetic profile.\n\nFor nutrient-specific recommendations, visit [healthpro.ai](https://healthpro.ai/nutrition/vitamin-d-deficiency).",
